</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">terests and financial stability will lead to a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">risk of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">increasing rent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">arrears</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> and homelessness </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">overall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">;</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">How private landlords will obtain information about the progress of their te</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">nants claims for housing costs; and,</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">Assisting tenants to manage with monthly budgeting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.4. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> acknowledge that the government has listened to stakeholders like ourselves; there are further issues to be addressed as outlined above. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he RLA agree that the objective of helping tenants manage their financial affairs is a laudable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">one.  However, this c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">omes at considerable risk.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Key p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">oints we would like the C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ommittee to consider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The need for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> clear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> communication</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> DWP, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">andlords and Local Authorities</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ast year the RLA and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Scottish Association of Landlords (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SAL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> conducted a survey of member</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s to assess attitudes towards Universal Credit. Between 22</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> October and 5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> November 2012, 1,023 landlords from across the UK took part in the survey.  Results showed that 65.2 per cent of respondents do not support the Government’s plans for universal credit</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would urge the Government to be open in their communication with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">private landlords regarding Universal Credit to offer reassurance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to attempt to change this negative perception</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  With the demand for social housing at an all-time high</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> benefit customers are increasingly being encouraged to look to the Private rented sect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or for an alternative to council or hous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing association accommodation.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The needs, worries and views of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Landlords must be considered</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by DWP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the housing costs part of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Universal Credit is to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be successful. If </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">andlords decide that they will not support th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e welfare changes the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">less well-off </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tenants will suffer due to a lack of housing options available to them. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This will simply put more pressure on an already</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> over stretched housing supply.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Landlords</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> must feel supported through this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transition of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">budgeting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">responsibility being given to the tenant and must feel able to access the help and support that they may need if things don’t work out. At the moment Universal Credit is a major worry for Landlords - the Gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rnment cannot ignore this fact and they must pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vide a resource that can accommoda</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">te for challenges and queries.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We feel that Landlords should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able to see how a claim is progressing. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The current proposals offer no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provision for landlords to c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heck that a claim has been made and there is no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">notification system so that landlords know that a c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">laim for housing costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is actually being paid, which could lead to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> further</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> apprehension in the sector.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">4.2.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Lack of clarity around the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">‘guidance’ that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold"> will replace regulation</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2.1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The RLA will o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bvio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">usly strive to support its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> members through this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">period of transition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the RLA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and othe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">andlord</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">trade </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">associations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> can only do this w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ith clear guidelines.  This will present a challenge as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the existing system of regulations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">begins</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to disappear.  Decisions as to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">payment will be made</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will be based</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> individually on a case-by-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">case basis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">according to guidance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If Landlords cannot access information about progress of claims then they will not be willing to take claimants on as tenant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s in the first place.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2.2. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We feel that too much </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">depend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on how efficient</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DWP administers the new system. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Landlords may have to wait longer for payment with increased risk of d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">efault. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The greater interval between payments, however, poses r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">isks. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is not at all clear </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">how advance payments will work.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2.3. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Another concern for the RLA and its members is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">huge risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that comes with having</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> new</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">scheme heavily dependent on as yet untried computer systems. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Given that the intention is for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Unive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rsal Credit system to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be digital when possible </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this is understandably leaving us wondering how this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will all work out in practice.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2.4. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We feel that until these uncertainties are addressed by government and tangible guidance is offered around housing co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sts and payment of rent within </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Universal Credit, l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">andlords will continue to be wary of the welfare changes. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.3. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Lack of protection</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold"> for l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">andlord’s interests and financial stability</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3.1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We feel that there is a common misconception that Landlords in the private rented sector are profiteering from housing benefit. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is not the case. According to DCLG's most recent Landlord Survey from 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">79 per cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of all landlords earned less than a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> quarter of their income from letting properties in the private rented sector with 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1 per cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of all landlords earning no income at all.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We therefore feel it unfair that under the new proposals there are no means of redress for landlords if things go wro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng or no rights of appeal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> potentially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">andlords could be left worse off than under the current system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We feel that the need for security of income on the landlord’s part</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is still an issue on which private landlords at large require reassurance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Important</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly, for the PRS the Government is pursuing a policy of using Universal Credit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to improve financial responsibility and financial ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nagement skills on the part of c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">laimants.  Whilst we feel that this is a worthwhile exercise in all other parts of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a claimant’s life, a home is the one thing that needs to be stable for the individual to prosper.  Simulating a monthly salary to benefits claimant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s is a risky strategy when a significant number </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will have bee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n used to weekly rent payments. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Currently, p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ayment of different benefits at different times of the month also helps these tenants to budget. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The long wait between payments and inexperience of money management with benefit claimants could have serious implications on bot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h the landlord and the tenant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3.3. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is not fair to expect that a private landlord will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be able to absorb the cost and risk of mounting rent arrears compared with a large social landlord as many simply do not operate on that scale or have resources as back up when things go wrong</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Most importantly, they do not have any public subsidy for providing housing for those tenants who would normally rent with a social landlord. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3.4. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We appreciate that the intention is that those who cannot manage their own financial affairs or are unl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ikely to pay rent should be identified as being vulnerable at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the outset and arrangements will t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> made which can include direct payment to the landlord.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> system of vulnerability should be assessed according to the tenant’s interest of keeping a ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of over their head and the landlord’s interest to receive the money, as well as the public interest of making sure that the benefit is u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sed for its intended purpose. We do question how robust these mechanics currently are.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">4.4.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">The greater risk of incr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">easing rent a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">rrears and homelessness overall</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">4.4.1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> introduction of the Local Housing Allowance and the resulting switch to paying benefit to the tenant instead of direct to the landlord has already had profound implications and landlords have reported increasing problems with arrears.  This ca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n only get w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">orse when Universal Credit is rolled out nationally and we would urge the government to listen to the concerns of our members. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We remain strongly of the view that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the tenant should be offered the choice to receive their housing cots directly or for them to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be paid directly to the landlord.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.5. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Monthly payments</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.5.1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have concerns for tenants who could face budgetary challenges as all of their benefit payments are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">combined into one monthly sum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The long wait between payments and inexperience of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">money management could have serious implications on both the landlord and the tenant.   This could lead to the tenant not allocating and saving enough money to pay the rent and getting into debt and rent arrears.  It is essential therefore that the local s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ervice framework which is intended to provide budgetary support for claimants is designed with the private sector in mind not just the social sector.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.6. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Emphasis on the social sector</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.6.1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We also feel that there is a lot of emphasis on ensuring that the social sector is prepared for the changes that will come with Universal Credit and how they will support their vulnerable tenants. This sector has the support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to ensure tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t they are delivering the programme as a partnership.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The private rented sector must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be incorporated into these local delivery partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> effectively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to prevent landlords from feeling disengaged.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Private landlords</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are very much a part of the local prov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ision of housing for the most vulnerable at a time when demand for social housing is high an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d supply low. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o lose their support in the long term would have detrimental consequences on vulnerable tenants.  A consistent approach a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cross all authorities is nee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ded –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not a postcode lottery.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.       </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> around Universal Credit</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.1.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would like to recommend the fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">llowing to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">quiry:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment should consider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the views of l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">andlords if the housing costs part of Universal Credit is to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">successful.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would urge the Government to be open in their communication with private landlords regarding Universal Credit to offer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">information and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reassurance to attempt to change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the current negative perception.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">support l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">andlords </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">through the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> transition of responsibility being given to the tenant and provide a resource that can accommodate for challenges and queries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> once Universal Credit is eventually rolled out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Local Services F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ramework has a vital role to pla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y in the private </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rented sector.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Landlords should be able to see how a cl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aim is progressing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clear </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">guidance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is required for DWP staff.  We believe that the guidance in the public domain around the issue of vulnerability is drafted too generally if it is to be used beyond</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the current P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">athfinders. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At the moment we feel that it is too open to interpretation due to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> loose nature of the ‘guidance’ rathe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r than implementing regulation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">look at how they might implement means of redress for Landlords who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">xperiencing late or no payment of re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt. G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consider how to protect the landlord’s interest and security of income </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">once Universal Credit is rolled out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 47.12pt; padding-left:2.53pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We feel strongly that the tenant should be offered the choice to receive their housing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ts directly or for them to be paid directly to the landlord.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6.       </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The longer term effects of Welfare Reforms </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.1.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We feel that the welfare changes provide an opportunity to take a wider view on housing supply and ways to ensure that landlords</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the private rented sector remain willing to continue to provide housing to benefit claimants who are out of work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or in work but on a low income.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.2.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In terms of the amount of housing costs payable we recognise that the transfer of LHA into Univers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al Credit is relatively seamless with no changes being made to how the rates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are calculated. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, we are concerned that by no longer linking local housing allowance rates to market rents there</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are two key wider implications:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Those private landlord</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s who only rent their properties to benefit claimants because of demand for low rent housing in their areas will not feel there is any incentive to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> continue to invest if the rates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o not rise with market rates. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This will then add to the already shortage of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> affordable rental accommodatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n in the private rented sector.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Housing conditions will be compromised if landlords are not able to increase rent in line with other market rents and in a climate where the cost of living is rising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This will affect the way </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">landlords maintain and repair their properties if they do not have the mone</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y to spend on their properties.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.3.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We feel that the longer term willingness of private landlords to continue to rent to benefit claimants will be co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mpromised as rents move away from market</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rents. We perceive the fixed one per cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> maximum rise in rates for 2013/14 and 2014/15 as well as the Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s previous policy of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> linking rises in rates to the Consumer P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ices I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ndex to be a major threat so far as sufficient provision of accommodation to claimants is concerned.  In many areas landlords are able to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">switch to non-benefit claimants;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this is something that we have repeatedly warned of and we can back this up by our re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cent survey findings. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.4.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This must be looked at in the wider context of housing supply. This is particularly true in L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ondon and other hotspots.  The G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment contend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s that it is, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in effect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a large purchaser who can use reductions in rates to infl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nce the market. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e question this assertion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> even if it is correct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it will not work in those areas where the landlord is able to let to a non-benefit claimant.  A far better way is to improve supply which will then let the market restrain rents. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.5.     </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A key function of housing benefit must be support those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> working on low wages. As Beverid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ge pointed out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it is essential that rates of housing benefit reflect local rental market conditions.  If you are on low wages and you do not get this extra sup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">port what is the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> point in working at all?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7.       </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Both</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the welfare reforms and the introduction of Universal Credit come with considerable risks. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is likely to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be a much higher level of arrears, an unwillingness of landlords </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to house benefit claimants (at a time when there is huge pressure on social housing), increased unwillingness by banks to lend for this kind of property (or increased interest rate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to reflect the risk), much higher levels of evictions and much greater hom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elessness.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.2.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We recognise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that this is an evolving system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What we do ask is that the C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommittee an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d the G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment do not forget the risk that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> private</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> landlords will be taking once Universal Credit is rolled out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> more widely and offer a workable system which encourages these landlords to participate in this important subsector of the housing market.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.3.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">More widely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e government needs to recognise the long term necessity of providing less well-off tenants w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ith sufficient support for their housing costs in light of increasing pressures on incomes. Supply side reforms are vita</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix I: RLA case study</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A member of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e RLA recently appealed to his L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Authority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">after he was owed a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> considerable amount of money from hi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s tenants in rent arrears.  The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> landlord has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over 50 tenants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and works wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">th several </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">landlord</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s and associations. Since November 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> he has personally lost over £3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,500 in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rent owed to him</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, from tenants claiming housing b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enefit:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Tenant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">’</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mother of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hree children, the tenant constantly falls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> into arrears with her</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The landlord </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> taken a loss on the arrears as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it is extremely difficult to get the rent arrears back from the tenant.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At one stage, </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he tenant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assisted by her mother in opening a bank </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">account for the rent to be paid into</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Unfortunately, this did not resolve the situation and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the temptation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of having large amounts of housing benefit provided to her directly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was too great</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and she lapsed into arrear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s once again, and reluctantly the landlord is now having to consider evicting her.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Tenant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This tenant was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">previously penniless and homeless</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The landlord accepted him as a tenant with his mother acting as a guarantor and controlling his rent payments and other household bills. Within a year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he tenant requested </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local Authority to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pay hi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s housing benefit directly to him. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">His mother repeatedl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y asked </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Local Authority not to allow this, but her requests were rejected. The landlord has now not been paid any rent since November 2012 and has instigated the eviction process.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Tenant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">This tenant fell into arrears as a consequence of having rent paid directly into his bank account. In addition, as recovering alcoholic, the temptation of the rent money being paid into his bank account proved too great and he subsequently suffered a relap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">se and is now drinking heavily once more. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix II: RLA/SAL Universal Credit S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">urvey</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 2012</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Last year the RLA and the Scottish Association of Landlords (SAL) conducted a survey of members to assess attitudes towards Universal Credit. Between 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2nd October and 5th November 2012, 1,023 landlords from across the UK took part in the survey.  Results showed that 65.2 per cent of respondents do not support the Governme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">nt’s plans for universal credit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">The full results from the survey can be found at: </span><a href="http://news.rla.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/universal-credit.rla-sal-survey-results-and-comments.051112.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://news.rla.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/universal-credit.rla-sal-survey-results-and-comments.051112.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">11</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1">